Exercise of Surfaces (II) in SageMath - Differential Geometry¶

Raul Almuzara¶

Consider the surface $S$ which is the graph of the function

$$f(x,y) = 6x^2 + 3xy + y^2 + 8x^3 + 5y^3 + 7x^2y^2$$
In [1]:
var('x,y,t,u,v', domain='real')

a1 = 7
a2 = 5
a3 = 8
a4 = 1
a5 = 3
a6 = 6

f(x,y) = a6*x^2 + a5*x*y + a4*y^2 + a3*x^3 + a2*y^3 + a1*x^2*y^2

The parametrization is

$$x = u$$$$y = v$$$$z = f(x,y) = f(u,v)$$
In [2]:
S = ParametrizedSurface3D((u,v,f(u,v)),(u,v),name='S')

We define the piecewise curve $\gamma_0(t)$ (a square)

$$ \gamma_0(t) = \begin{cases} (2t+3,-1),\qquad t\in[-2,-1]\\ \\ (1,2t+1),\qquad t\in[-1,0]\\ \\ (1-2t,1),\qquad t\in[0,1]\\ \\ (-1,3-2t),\qquad t\in[1,2] \end{cases} $$
In [3]:
gamma0first(t) = (2*t+3 , -1)
gamma0second(t) = (1 , 2*t+1)
gamma0third(t) = (1-2*t , 1)
gamma0fourth(t) = (-1 , 3-2*t)

And we define $\gamma(t) = (\gamma_0(t) , f(\gamma_0(t)))$ (piecewise)

In [4]:
gammafirst(t) = (gamma0first(t)[0] , gamma0first(t)[1], f(gamma0first(t)[0],gamma0first(t)[1]))
gammasecond(t) = (gamma0second(t)[0] , gamma0second(t)[1], f(gamma0second(t)[0],gamma0second(t)[1]))
gammathird(t) = (gamma0third(t)[0] , gamma0third(t)[1], f(gamma0third(t)[0],gamma0third(t)[1]))
gammafourth(t) = (gamma0fourth(t)[0] , gamma0fourth(t)[1], f(gamma0fourth(t)[0],gamma0fourth(t)[1]))

The surface

$$B = \{(u,v,f(u,v)) | -1\leq u,v\leq 1\}$$

is the part of $S$ above the square $A = [-1,1]^2$.

In [5]:
S.plot((-1,1),(-1,1))
Out[5]:

Question 1: Compute (numerically) $\iint_B K$, where $K$ is the Gaussian curvature.¶

Since $B$ is an elemental region of $S$ and we have a plane region $A$ such that the restriction of $\mathbf{x}(u,v)=(u,v,f(u,v))$ in $A$ is a homeomorphism, we may express $\iint_B K$ as following:

$$ \iint_B K = \iint_A K_{\mathbf{x}}\sqrt{\det\mathbf{I}_{\mathbf{x}}}\,\text{d} u\,\text{d} v $$

The Gaussian curvature obtained with gauss_curvature is

In [6]:
K = (S.gauss_curvature()).factor()
K.show()
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}-\frac{588 \, u^{2} v^{2} - 672 \, u^{3} - 420 \, v^{3} - 168 \, u^{2} - 1272 \, u v - 28 \, v^{2} - 96 \, u - 360 \, v - 15}{{\left(196 \, u^{4} v^{2} + 196 \, u^{2} v^{4} + 672 \, u^{3} v^{2} + 420 \, u^{2} v^{3} + 576 \, u^{4} + 84 \, u^{3} v + 392 \, u^{2} v^{2} + 84 \, u v^{3} + 225 \, v^{4} + 576 \, u^{3} + 144 \, u^{2} v + 90 \, u v^{2} + 60 \, v^{3} + 153 \, u^{2} + 84 \, u v + 13 \, v^{2} + 1\right)}^{2}}\]

And the determinant of the first fundamental form is given by area_form:

In [7]:
detI = (S.area_form()).factor()
detI.show()
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}\sqrt{{\left| {\left(196 \, u^{2} + 225\right)} v^{4} + 576 \, u^{4} + 12 \, {\left(35 \, u^{2} + 7 \, u + 5\right)} v^{3} + 576 \, u^{3} + {\left(196 \, u^{4} + 672 \, u^{3} + 392 \, u^{2} + 90 \, u + 13\right)} v^{2} + 153 \, u^{2} + 12 \, {\left(7 \, u^{3} + 12 \, u^{2} + 7 \, u\right)} v + 1 \right|}}\]

We integrate the product with monte_carlo_integral:

In [8]:
integralK = monte_carlo_integral(K*detI,[-1,-1],[1,1],500000,algorithm='vegas')[0]
show(integralK)
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}-5.593612139687834\]

Question 2: Compute $\int_{-2}^2 \kappa_{\gamma,g}^S ||\gamma'(t)||\ \text{d}t$ where $\kappa_{\gamma,g}^S$ is the geodesic curvature.¶

From the definition of $\kappa_{\gamma,g}^S$, we deduce

$$\kappa_{\gamma,g}^S=\frac{\langle\mathbf{t}'_{\gamma},\mathbf{n}_{\gamma}^S\rangle}{||{\gamma'(t)}||} \implies \kappa_{\gamma,g}^S ||\gamma'(t)|| = \langle\mathbf{t}'_{\gamma},\mathbf{n}_{\gamma}^S\rangle$$

where $\mathbf{t}_{\gamma}$ is the tangent vector on the curve $\gamma$ and $$\mathbf{n}_{\gamma}^S = \mathbf{N}_{\gamma}^S \times \mathbf{t}_{\gamma}$$ where $\mathbf{N}_{\gamma}^S$ is the normal vector on the curve $\gamma$ (with the appropriate substitution of coordinates from the original $u,v$ of the surface to the coordinates of the curve $\gamma$).

Since $\gamma(t)$ is a piecewise curve, we will compute the above objects and the integral in each of the 4 intervals:

  • Interval $[-2,-1]$:
In [9]:
N_uppercase1 = S.normal_vector(normalized=True).apply_map(factor).subs(u=gammafirst(t)[0],v=gammafirst(t)[1]) #Uppercase N on the curve
dgamma1 = gammafirst.derivative(t) #Derivative of gamma
tv1 = dgamma1.normalized() #Tangent vector
n_lowercase1 = N_uppercase1.cross_product(tv1) #Lowercase n
tvprime1 = tv1.derivative(t) #Derivative of the tangent vector
integrand1 = tvprime1*n_lowercase1 #Scalar product <t',n> to be integrated
integral1 = monte_carlo_integral(integrand1(t),[-2],[-1],100000,algorithm='vegas')[0] #Integral in [-2,-1]
  • Interval $[-1,0]$:
In [10]:
N_uppercase2 = S.normal_vector(normalized=True).apply_map(factor).subs(u=gammasecond(t)[0],v=gammasecond(t)[1]) #Uppercase N on the curve
dgamma2 = gammasecond.derivative(t) #Derivative of gamma
tv2 = dgamma2.normalized() #Tangent vector
n_lowercase2 = N_uppercase2.cross_product(tv2) #Lowercase n
tvprime2 = tv2.derivative(t) #Derivative of the tangent vector
integrand2 = tvprime2*n_lowercase2 #Scalar product <t',n> to be integrated
integral2 = monte_carlo_integral(integrand2(t),[-1],[0],100000,algorithm='vegas')[0] #Integral in [-1,0]
  • Interval $[0,1]$:
In [11]:
N_uppercase3 = S.normal_vector(normalized=True).apply_map(factor).subs(u=gammathird(t)[0],v=gammathird(t)[1]) #Uppercase N on the curve
dgamma3 = gammathird.derivative(t) #Derivative of gamma
tv3 = dgamma3.normalized() #Tangent vector
n_lowercase3 = N_uppercase3.cross_product(tv3) #Lowercase n
tvprime3 = tv3.derivative(t) #Derivative of the tangent vector
integrand3 = tvprime3*n_lowercase3 #Scalar product <t',n> to be integrated
integral3 = monte_carlo_integral(integrand3(t),[0],[1],100000,algorithm='vegas')[0] #Integral in [0,1]
  • Interval $[1,2]$:
In [12]:
N_uppercase4 = S.normal_vector(normalized=True).apply_map(factor).subs(u=gammafourth(t)[0],v=gammafourth(t)[1]) #Uppercase N on the curve
dgamma4 = gammafourth.derivative(t) #Derivative of gamma
tv4 = dgamma4.normalized() #Tangent field
n_lowercase4 = N_uppercase4.cross_product(tv4) #Lowercase n
tvprime4 = tv4.derivative(t) #Derivative of the tangent vector
integrand4 = tvprime4*n_lowercase4 #Scalar product <t',n> to be integrated
integral4 = monte_carlo_integral(integrand4(t),[1],[2],100000,algorithm='vegas')[0] #Integral in [1,2]

And the total integral is the sum of the integrals in each of the intervals:

In [13]:
integralgeo = integral1 + integral2 + integral3 + integral4
show(integralgeo)
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}4.691814766020854\]

Question 3: Compute $\lambda_{t_0} = \measuredangle(\mathbf{t}^{-}(t_0),\mathbf{t}^{+}(t_0))$, $t_0 = -2,-1,0,1$.¶

$\mathbf{t}^{-}(t_0)$ is the value of $\mathbf{t}(t_0)$ immediately to the left of $t_0$ and $\mathbf{t}^{+}(t_0)$ is the value of $\mathbf{t}(t_0)$ immediately to the right of $t_0$ (observe that $\mathbf{t}^{-}(-2)=\mathbf{t}^{-}(2)$).¶

The angle between $\mathbf{t}^{-}(t_0)$ and $\mathbf{t}^{+}(t_0)$ is

$$\lambda_{t_0} = \arccos\left(\frac{\langle\mathbf{t}^{-}(t_0),\mathbf{t}^{+}(t_0)\rangle}{||\mathbf{t}^{-}(t_0)||\cdot||\mathbf{t}^{+}(t_0)||}\right)$$
  • For $t_0=-2$: We use the property that $\mathbf{t}^{-}(-2)=\mathbf{t}^{-}(2)$ because the period of the curve is $4$. Then, we compute $\mathbf{t}^{-}(-2)$ from the fourth piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [1,2]$) and we compute $\mathbf{t}^{+}(-2)$ from the first piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [-2,-1]$).
In [14]:
tv1minus = gammafourth(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=2) #Tangent vector to the left of t0 = -2
tv1plus = gammafirst(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=-2) #Tangent vector to the right of t0 = -2
scalarproduct1 = tv1minus*tv1plus #Scalar product of the two above tangent vectors
normt1minus = tv1minus.norm() #Norm of the tangent vector to the left of t0 = -2
normt1plus = tv1plus.norm() #Norm of the tangent vector to the right of t0 = -2

lambda1 = N(arccos((scalarproduct1)/(normt1minus*normt1plus))) #Numerical approximation of the desired angle at t0 = -2
show(lambda1)
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}2.82823196987659\]
  • For $t_0=-1$: We compute $\mathbf{t}^{-}(-1)$ from the first piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [-2,-1]$) and we compute $\mathbf{t}^{+}(-1)$ from the second piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [-1,0]$).
In [15]:
tv2minus = gammafirst(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=-1) #Tangent vector to the left of t0 = -1
tv2plus = gammasecond(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=-1) #Tangent vector to the right of t0 = -1
scalarproduct2 = tv2minus*tv2plus #Scalar product of the two above tangent vectors
normt2minus = tv2minus.norm() #Norm of the tangent vector to the left of t0 = -1
normt2plus = tv2plus.norm() #Norm of the tangent vector to the right of t0 = -1

lambda2 = N(arccos((scalarproduct2)/(normt2minus*normt2plus))) #Numerical approximation of the desired angle at t0 = -1
show(lambda2)
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}0.464099944294886\]
  • For $t_0=0$: We compute $\mathbf{t}^{-}(0)$ from the second piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [-1,0]$) and we compute $\mathbf{t}^{+}(0)$ from the third piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [0,1]$).
In [16]:
tv3minus = gammasecond(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=0) #Tangent field to the left of t0 = 0
tv3plus = gammathird(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=0) #Tangent field to the right of t0 = 0
scalarproduct3 = tv3minus*tv3plus #Scalar product of the two above tangent vectors
normt3minus = tv3minus.norm() #Norm of the tangent field to the left of t0 = 0
normt3plus = tv3plus.norm() #Norm of the tangent field to the right of t0 = 0

show(lambda3)
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}3.10665893221606\]
  • For $t_0=1$: We compute $\mathbf{t}^{-}(1)$ from the third piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [0,1]$) and we compute $\mathbf{t}^{+}(1)$ from the fourth piece of $\gamma(t)$ (with $t\in [1,2]$).
In [17]:
tv4minus = gammathird(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=1) #Tangent vector to the left of t0 = 1
tv4plus = gammafourth(t).derivative(t).normalized().subs(t=1) #Tangent vector to the right of t0 = 1
scalarproduct4 = tv4minus*tv4plus #Scalar product of the two above tangent vectors
normt4minus = tv4minus.norm() #Norm of the tangent vector to the left of t0 = 1
normt4plus = tv4plus.norm() #Norm of the tangent vector to the right of t0 = 1

Question 4: Sum the above values and compare the result with $2\pi$.¶

We compute the sum

$$\iint_B K + \int_{-2}^2 \kappa_{\gamma,g}^S ||\gamma'(t)||\ \text{d}t + \lambda_{-2} + \lambda_{-1} + \lambda_{0} + \lambda_{1}$$
In [18]:
totalsum = integralK + integralgeo + lambda1 + lambda2 + lambda3 + lambda4
show(totalsum)
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}6.28322857896544\]

We compare the result with $2\pi$

In [19]:
show(N(2*pi))
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}6.28318530717959\]

The (absolute) difference between both values is

In [20]:
show(N(abs(2*pi-totalsum)))
\[\newcommand{\Bold}[1]{\mathbf{#1}}0.0000432717858496190\]

The absolute error is of the order of $10^{-5}$. Clearly, they are very similar. This is to be expected since the local Gauss-Bonnet theorem guarantees that this sum is $2\pi$, and we have verified this numerically in this particular example. The small deviation from $2\pi$ may be due to small errors made in the numerical integration or small numerical errors that accumulate when performing multiple operations with limited numerical accuracy in SageMath.

Question 5: Plot the surface and some geodesics $\gamma_{\mathbf{0},\mathbf{u}_{\alpha}}:(-1,1)\rightarrow S$ starting at the origin with direction $\mathbf{u}_{\alpha} = (\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,0)$.¶

We use geodesics_numerical to compute geodesics numerically. We will obtain geodesics $\gamma_{\mathbf{p},\mathbf{v}}$, defined in $[c,d]$, where $\mathbf{p}=\mathbf{x}(u_0,v_0)$ and $\mathbf{v}=a\mathbf{x}_u(u_0,v_0)+b\mathbf{x}_v(u_0,v_0)$. The inputs are $[u_0,v_0]$, $[a,b]$ and $[c,d,p]$, where $p$ is the number of subdivision points used.

In our case, $u_0=v_0=0$ and $\mathbf{p}=\mathbf{x}(0,0)=\mathbf{0}$

Furthermore, we have $\mathbf{x}(u,v)=(u,v,f(u,v))$, so

$$\mathbf{x}_u(u,v)=(1,0,\frac{\partial f}{\partial u}(u,v)) \implies \mathbf{x}_u(0,0)=(1,0,0)$$$$\mathbf{x}_v(u,v)=(0,1,\frac{\partial f}{\partial v}(u,v)) \implies \mathbf{x}_v(0,0)=(0,1,0)$$

Therefore,

$$\mathbf{v} = a(1,0,0) + b(0,1,0)$$

In order to obtain $\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{u}_{\alpha} = (\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,0)$, we choose $a=\cos\alpha$ and $b=\sin\alpha$. We will consider several angles: $\alpha = 0, \frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{3\pi}{4}, \pi, \frac{5\pi}{4}, \frac{3\pi}{2}, \frac{7\pi}{4}$

Since the parameter of $\gamma_{\mathbf{0},\mathbf{u}_{\alpha}}$ is defined in $(-1,1)$, we have $c=-1$ and $d=1$.

We fix $p=1000$ points.

Finally, we plot the geodesics along with the surface $S$.

  • In red, the geodesic with $\alpha=0$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{0} = \left(1,0,0\right)$
  • In blue, the geodesic with $\alpha=\frac{\pi}{4}$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{\frac{\pi}{4}} = \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},0\right)$
  • In orange, the geodesic with $\alpha=\frac{\pi}{2}$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{\frac{\pi}{2}} = \left(0,1,0\right)$
  • In green, the geodesic with $\alpha=\frac{3\pi}{4}$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{\frac{3\pi}{4}} = \left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},0\right)$
  • In black, the geodesic with $\alpha=\pi$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{\pi} = \left(-1,0,0\right)$
  • In yellow, the geodesic with $\alpha=\frac{5\pi}{4}$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{\frac{5\pi}{4}} = \left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},0\right)$
  • In purple, the geodesic with $\alpha=\frac{3\pi}{2}$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{\frac{3\pi}{2}} = \left(0,-1,0\right)$
  • In cyan, the geodesic with $\alpha=\frac{7\pi}{4}$, i.e., $\mathbf{u}_{\frac{7\pi}{4}} = \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},0\right)$
In [21]:
L1 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(0),sin(0)],[-1,1,1000])
L2 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(pi/4),sin(pi/4)],[-1,1,1000])
L3 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(pi/2),sin(pi/2)],[-1,1,1000])
L4 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(3*pi/4),sin(3*pi/4)],[-1,1,1000])
L5 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(pi),sin(pi)],[-1,1,1000])
L6 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(5*pi/4),sin(5*pi/4)],[-1,1,1000])
L7 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(3*pi/2),sin(3*pi/2)],[-1,1,1000])
L8 = S.geodesics_numerical([0,0],[cos(7*pi/4),sin(7*pi/4)],[-1,1,1000])
